2. Create a new categorical variable âobesity_levelâ from BMI

chs_merge <- as.data.frame(chs_merge)
chs_merge <-
  chs_merge %>%
  mutate(obesity_level = case_when(chs_merge$bmi < 14  ~ 'Underweight', 
                              chs_merge$bmi >= 14 & chs_merge$bmi < 22  ~ 'Normal', 
                              chs_merge$bmi >= 22 & chs_merge$bmi < 24  ~ 'Overweight', 
                              chs_merge$bmi >= 24  ~ 'Obese'))
chs_merge %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarise(min_bmi = min(bmi), 
            max_bmi = max(bmi),
            n_bmi = n())
# A tibble: 4 Ã 4
  obesity_level min_bmi max_bmi n_bmi

3. Create variable âsmoke_gas_exposureâ

chs_merge <-
  chs_merge %>%
  mutate(smoke_gas_exposure = case_when(
    chs_merge$smoke == 0 & chs_merge$gasstove == 0 ~ 'No exposure',
    chs_merge$smoke == 0 & chs_merge$gasstove == 1 ~ 'Gas exposure',
    chs_merge$smoke == 1 & chs_merge$gasstove == 0 ~ 'Smoke exposure',
    chs_merge$smoke == 1 & chs_merge$gasstove == 1 ~ 'Smoke & gas exposure'))

Visualization

1. BMI vs.Â FEV by townname

library(ggplot2)

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = bmi, y = fev, group = townname)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev, color = townname)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color='black') +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  facet_wrap( ~ townname, nrow= 3) +
  ggtitle("BMI vs FEV by Town") +
  xlab("BMI") +
  ylab("FEV (mL)")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

For each town in the CHS communities, there appears to be a positive linear association between FEV and BMI. Some towns have stronger association than others, however it is hugely impacted by outliers.

2. Stacked histograms of FEV by BMI category and FEV by smoke/gas exposure.

  1. By BMI categroy
chs_merge$obesity_level <- factor(chs_merge$obesity_level, levels = c("Underweight", "Normal", "Overweight", "Obese"))

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fev, fill = obesity_level)) + 
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha = 0.8, binwidth = 100, color="black") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Reds") +
  ggtitle("FEV by BMI Categroy") +
  xlab("FEV (mL)") +
  ylab("Count")

From the stacked histogram, we can see that the distribution of FEV is slightly more left skewed in overweight and obese population than underweight and normal population.

  1. By smoke gas exposure
chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = fev, fill = smoke_gas_exposure)) + 
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha = 0.8, binwidth = 100, color="black") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Greens") +
  ggtitle("FEV by smoke/gas Exposure") +
  xlab("FEV (mL)") +
  ylab("Count")

Based on the stacked histogram of FEV by smoke/gas exposure, there is no obvious difference in distribution between the four groups, however there the gas stove exposure only group is the most abundant.

3. Bar chart of BMI by smoke/gas exposure

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = obesity_level, fill = smoke_gas_exposure)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") +
  ggtitle("BMI by smoke/gas Exposure") +
  xlab("Obesity level") +
  ylab("Count") +
  labs(fill="Exposure")

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = obesity_level, fill = smoke_gas_exposure)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent") +
  ggtitle("BMI by smoke/gas Exposure (100% stacked)") +
  xlab("Obesity level") +
  ylab("Count") +
  labs(fill="Exposure")

The bar chart of BMI by smoke and gas expsure shows that gas stove only takes up the largest proportion in all BMI categories, followed by no exposure, smoke and gas exposure, and smoke exposure only. From the 100% stacked bar chart we can see that the frequency of each type of exposure is approximately the same across all BMI categories. Interestingly, compared to normal and underweight population, a larger proportion in the overweight and obese population is exposed to smoke.

4. Statistical summary graphs of FEV by BMI and FEV by smoke/gas exposure category.

chs_merge %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = obesity_level, y = fev, color = obesity_level)) +
    stat_summary(fun.data = mean_sdl, geom = "pointrange") +
    stat_summary(fun.data = mean_sdl, geom = "errorbar")+
  labs (title = "Statisitical Summary of FEV by BMI")

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = bmi, y = fev)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = bmi, y = fev)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color='red') +
  ggtitle("BMI vs FEV scatter plot") +
  xlab("BMI") +
  ylab("FEV (mL)")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

According to the box plot and scatter plot between BMI and FEV, FEV seems to be positively associated with BMI. The box plot between FEV and smoke gas stove exposure shows no apparent difference in mean of FEV across all exposure groups.

5. A leaflet map showing the concentrations of PM2.5 mass in each of the CHS communities.

library(leaflet)

temp.pal <- colorFactor(c('lightgreen','darkred'), domain = chs_merge$pm25_mass) 
  
leaflet(chs_merge) %>% 
  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>%
  addCircles(
    lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon, color = ~temp.pal(pm25_mass),
    opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1, radius = 100) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=temp.pal, chs_merge$pm25_mass,
            title='PM2.5', opacity=1)

The highest PM2.5 mass is located in San Bernardino and the lowest PM2.5 mass up North in Santa Barbara and Santa Maria.

6. Choose a visualization to examine whether PM2.5 mass is associated with FEV.

chs_merge %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = pm25_mass, y = fev, color = pm25_mass)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = pm25_mass, y = fev)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color='black') +
  ggtitle("FEV vs PM2.5 mass") +
  xlab("PM2.5 mass") +
  ylab("FEV (mL)")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

chs_mean <-
  chs_merge %>%
  group_by(townname) %>%
  mutate(fev = mean(fev))

chs_mean %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = pm25_mass, y = fev, color = factor(townname))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black") +
  ggtitle("Average FEV by towns vs PM2.5 mass")  +
  xlab("PM2.5") +
  ylab("Average FEV")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

chs_merge %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = smoke_gas_exposure, y = fev, color = smoke_gas_exposure)) +
    stat_summary(fun.data = mean_sdl, geom = "pointrange") +
    stat_summary(fun.data = mean_sdl, geom = "errorbar")+
  labs (title = "Statisitical Summary of FEV by smoke/gas Exposure") +
  scale_x_discrete(guide = guide_axis(n.dodge=2))

By the FEV vs.Â PM2.5 mass scatter plot, we see that the slope for the regression line is slightly negative. However, if we stratify by town and regress the mean FEV of each town to PM2.5 mass, negative association between FEV and PM 2.5 mass becomes more evident.
